1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,000
 So now we're going to bring this all together and we're going to build a simple, programmable, flexible programmable central processor, building it all with gates.

2
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:18,000
 It's not going to be very sophisticated, but it's going to be a programmable processor.

3
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:26,000
 So let's go back to the beginning of my Python class and look at this picture again,

4
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:33,000
 where we have a central processing unit that has registers and arithmetic logic units and it processes instructions.

5
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:37,000
 And in the main memory, we have the code and data.

6
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:42,000
 And so when we write a program, we kind of are putting ourselves into that main memory.

7
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:48,000
 The central processor asks, what next? And that says, give me the next instruction.

8
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:55,000
 And that next instruction is a series of binary numbers, zeros and ones, coming out of the memory of the computer.

9
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:59,000
 Then it decodes that instruction and it says, what am I going to do?

10
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:06,000
 Maybe load some, load a value from memory, store a value from memory, perform a calculation inside the central processing unit.

11
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:10,000
 And then when that's done, the central processing unit says, give me the next instruction.

12
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
 And then the main memory gives the next instruction.

13
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:22,000
 And so this is an oversimplified, generic computer, suitable for a very beginning Python programming class.

14
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:28,000
 But let's use a little more advanced terminology that you will eventually hear.

15
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:33,000
 So inside the CPU, there's a thing called the arithmetic logic unit.

16
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:36,000
 We call it the ALU. It's like the adder code.

17
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,000
 We've already built a three bit adder. That would be in the arithmetic logic unit.

18
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:46,000
 When they mean logic, they mean comparison, like if tests, if tests are checked, like is X less than zero?

19
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:49,000
 That's part of the logic, part of arithmetic logic.

20
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:58,000
 Registers are temporary places to store data in the CPU that does not require going to and from memory all the time.

21
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:05,000
 We've already built a register. We built a three bit latch, which I also told you was a three bit register.

22
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:11,000
 And then what we have is programs and they come from the memory.

23
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:21,000
 And so the memory has a series of program instructions. The CPU has what's called a program counter.

24
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:27,000
 And it retrieves the next instruction, decides what kind of instruction it is,

25
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:36,000
 and then sends signals to the registers and the ALU, whether it's loading data or storing data or making computations.

26
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:41,000
 Coming up very soon, we're going to actually design a simple CPU that has machine language.

27
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:47,000
 It's going to be a complete architecture. It will have a machine language and an assembly language completely defined.

28
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,000
 And we will write programs in this little machine language.

29
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:56,000
 Now, it's called the CDC 8512 because when I was young and just starting out,

30
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:02,000
 I programmed on a computer called the Control Data Corporation CDC 6500.

31
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:07,000
 And back when the computer museum in Seattle was open, they had a running one of these things.

32
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:10,000
 And I have a video which I will share with you.

33
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:17,000
 Unfortunately, with the passing of Paul L. and that museum closed, but that's unfortunate.

34
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:22,000
 So I've seen one running recently. I've got some video and I will share that with you.

35
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:24,000
 But that's not what we're doing right now.

36
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:36,000
 I'm just telling you that what we're doing right now is a step toward building a real live full function CPU with machine language and data, et cetera.

37
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:41,000
 So but now we're going to build a really, really simple CPU.

38
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:44,000
 It's going to have one register. It's a three bit latch.

39
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:51,000
 It's going to have two machine instructions that we can inform the CPU what we want done.

40
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:57,000
 It has a clock that happens every second. So it runs one of two instructions every second.

41
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:05,000
 The zero instruction against machine language clears the latch and the one instruction tells the latch to add one to itself.

42
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,000
 And like I said, this is going to happen once per second.

43
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 And we can submit a zero instruction or a one instruction once per second.

44
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:20,000
 So we're going to have this built and it's going to run on our emulator.

45
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:26,000
 This is the CPU. The emulator has a clock. It has a three bit latch, which is our register.

46
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:31,000
 Then it has an adder. One of the operands to the adder is the output of the latch.

47
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:35,000
 The other operand to the adder is a one hard coded one.

48
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:38,000
 And then you take the output of the adder.

49
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:44,000
 Now, before we had run this straight into the latch so that it would just add one every time.

50
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:48,000
 But now what we have is some decoding logic.

51
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:53,000
 So if the instruction is zero, recall the latch is supposed to be set to zero.

52
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:57,000
 If the instruction is one, we're adding one to the latch.

53
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:01,000
 Every clock pulse and that clock is going up and down once per second.

54
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 The part that we've added here from the previous example is this logic.

55
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:09,000
 When you look at real CPUs, you're going to see that they have a series of control logic.

56
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:11,000
 And what does the control logic do?

57
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:16,000
 It reads the next instruction from memory and it does what's called decoding it.

58
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:20,000
 And then it distributes signals to give orders to the rest of it.

59
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:28,000
 And so in this case, what's going to happen is this AND gate is going to block the output.

60
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:35,000
 Because we just put ANDs. We are running the one, two, and four column of the sum through the AND gate.

61
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:40,000
 And then we're hard coding zero, the instruction zero to the other inputs of the three AND gates.

62
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 And so the output of those AND gates, if the instruction is zero, is zero.

63
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:48,000
 No matter what the other inputs are from the adder.

64
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:51,000
 So we'll start this with instruction zero.

65
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:56,000
 So every time the clock goes, the inputs to the latch are all zeros.

66
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 Because the instruction input is a zero and zero in anything is a zero.

67
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:05,000
 So clock tick, tick, tick.

68
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:11,000
 Every time this clock is ticking, that latch is resetting, meaning copying zero from its inputs.

69
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 So the adder is like happily adding one to the zero, but that's it.

70
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:22,000
 Because the adder inputs are being blocked from coming back into the latch by the AND gates.

71
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:26,000
 So you see when the instruction is zero, the AND gates function as a block.

72
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 In effect, turning off the data going into the latch.

73
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:40,000
 Now we're going to switch the instruction to one and we wait one clock pulse.

74
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 So then what happens is the one instruction going to the three AND gates is no longer blocking data.

75
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:53,000
 So whatever the outputs are coming from the adder, are passing right through the gate.

76
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,000
 In this particular case, the adder has a four.

77
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:59,000
 That is presenting a four at the input.

78
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:03,000
 Four's column is a one and the two's column is a zero and the one's column is a zero.

79
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:09,000
 While the clock is low, that four is at the input to the register/latch.

80
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:15,000
 And then when the clock goes high, then we'll copy the four into the latch.

81
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:19,000
 In the beginning, you start with the instruction zero, the latch is zero, the adder is one,

82
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:24,000
 but the zero instruction is blocking data to go back into the latch.

83
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:27,000
 It's blocked because it's a zero instruction.

84
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:33,000
 On the other hand, if there is a one instruction, then this functions like a counter.

85
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:36,000
 That means every second it goes up by one.

86
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 So when the clock is high, it copies the input.

87
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:44,000
 Then the clock goes low, then the latch value goes to output, the adder adds one.

88
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:50,000
 Then as long as the instruction stays one and the clock goes high,

89
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:54,000
 the output of the adder is once again copied into the latch.

90
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,000
 So it's a very simple two instruction computer.

91
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:05,000
 We simply touch the instruction, we program this by touching the instruction value switch and setting it to zero or one.

92
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:07,000
 So this is a two instruction computer.

93
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:09,000
 What's missing?

94
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:16,000
 Well, really, it's really hard to build a CPU where you can reach in and touch a button

95
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 and have the instruction be the button that you touched.

96
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:22,000
 The clock rate is, you know, megahertz, not one hertz.

97
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:24,000
 And so you can't send the instruction.

98
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:30,000
 So really what you want is a flexible way to store and retrieve instructions

99
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:37,000
 so that the instructions can be presented to the CPU fast enough to keep up with the clock rate.

100
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:43,000
 So we really want a flexible, long sequence of many instructions executed one after another,

101
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:47,000
 which we would call software or a program.

102
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:53,000
 So next, we're going to think about how we might store sequences of instruction in the memory

103
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:58,000
 and then retrieve those instructions from the memory and then execute them in the CPU.

104
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:02,000
 Wait just a second.

105
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:08,000
 There were a lot of switches on the front of a class's computer in a video from an earlier lecture.

106
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 Yes, the earliest computers did have switches on the front to control program behavior.

107
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:30,000
 These switches often controlled conditional variables so program behavior could be changed

108
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:33,000
 while flipping a switch while the program was running.

109
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 Actually, those switches were more like the variables that could be changed on the front panel.

